@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{he}}" grammar="@HI{{he}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{he}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<dl>
<dt> (A) direction of motion
<ol>
<li> @N{{location}} @EM{{@HI{{he}}}}
</ol>
<dt> (B) recipient of an action
<ol>
<li> @N{{recipient}} @EM{{@HI{{he}}}}
</ol>
</dl>

<h2> Definition </h2>


<p>
@EM{{@HI{{he}}}} is used to indicate the direction in which someone is moving.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{itsu@KJ{{capital^metropolis}}@EM{{he}}@KJ{{going}}kimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      When are you going to Kyoto?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Strictly speaking, @HI{{ni}} indicates the destination.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{yoku kono @KJ{{consume^tea^store}}@EM{{ni}} @KJ{{come}}rundesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I often come to this coffee shop.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{he}}}} is used to indicate the recipient of an action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{outside^country}}niiru@KJ{{friend^accomplished}}@EM{{he}}@KJ{{hand^paper}}wo@KJ{{write}}ita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wrote a letter to a friend abroad.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{he}}}} can always be replaced by @HI{{ni}} except when it is followed by @HI{{no}}. In the example below
@HI{{ni}} cannot replace @EM{{@HI{{he}}}}, but @HI{{made}} can.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{nyu-yo-ku}}@EM{{he}}no@KJ{{convenience}}hamouarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There isn't any flight to New York any more.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

